===Etymology 1===
{{PIE root|en|twerḱ}}
Probably partly from both of the following:<ref>{{R:OED Online|pos=''n.{{sup|2}}''|noformat=1|id=164445|date=March 2010|nodot=1}}; {{R:Lexico|pos=n}}</ref>

* {{der|en|frm|retrenchement}}, {{m|frm|retranchement|t=removal of a portion from a larger whole; reduction of expenses}} (modern {{cog|fr|retranchement|t=deduction, subtraction}}), from {{m|frm|retrancher}}, {{m|frm|retranchier|t=to get rid of, remove completely; to remove a portion from a larger whole; to reduce expenses; to deprive (oneself) of}}{{nb...|retrencher, retrenchier|otherforms=1}} + {{m|frm|-ment|pos=suffix forming {{glossary|noun}}s usually of an action or a state resulting from an action}}. ''Retrancher'' and ''retranchier'' are derived from {{der|en|fro|re-|pos=prefix meaning ‘again, once more’}} + {{m|fro|tranchier}}, {{m|fro|trenchier|t=to cut}}{{nb...|trencher|otherforms=1}} (modern {{cog|fr|trancher|t=to slice}}); the further etymology is uncertain, but one possibility is that the Old French words are from {{der|en|la|truncāre}}, the {{glossary|present}} {{glossary|active}} {{glossary|infinitive}} of {{m|la|truncō|t=to mutilate by cutting off pieces; to truncate}}, from {{m|la|truncus|t=tree trunk; piece cut off}}, ultimately from {{der|en|ine-pro|*twerḱ-|t=to carve; to cut off, trim}}.
* {{suffix|en|retrench|t1=to cut down, reduce; to reduce expenses; to make (an employee) redundant|ment}}.

